In the end a groundbased farm that can use wire-transmission is probably less dangerous and more efficient than anything you can send out into an orbit.

By the way Tim, if you're ever interested in learning about astrobiology, there's a short, free course on Coursera from the univeristy of Edinborough. It actually covers the standards, and what techniques used to ensure things travelling to Mars or the other planets are up to the standards put out by the planetary protection guidelines. Astrobiology includes a lot of study of microbes on earth, usually extremeophiles, those that live in extreme environments, to help understand what could survive out there. Things like tardigrades and some bacteria can survive the extreme cold and radiation out in space. They deminstrated this by bolting a plate with a bunch of bacterial colonies to the outside of the ISS, and one strain did survive. It didn't grow, but it didn't die.
